00:53:37.275 --> 00:53:38.277
a beautiful urban place.

00:53:38.277 --> 00:53:40.610
But nonetheless, we live on
a farm So it's so fun for me

00:53:40.610 --> 00:53:43.026
to walk around New York and
think about, like, oh, my god,

00:53:43.026 --> 00:53:45.844
my dogs would be freaking
out if they were here.

00:53:45.844 --> 00:53:46.760
So a couple of things.

00:53:46.760 --> 00:53:49.880
And one, I'll just answer
the most extreme, sort

00:53:49.880 --> 00:53:52.330
of, extreme intensity
of the level.

00:53:52.330 --> 00:53:54.860
I have had clients who
literally taught their dog

00:53:54.860 --> 00:53:57.560
to wear a muzzle, not
because the dog needed it,

00:53:57.560 --> 00:54:00.512
because people don't pet
dogs with muzzles on.

00:54:00.512 --> 00:54:02.720
Which is amazing, because
when they have a muzzle on,

00:54:02.720 --> 00:54:05.579
they're safe, theoretically.

00:54:05.579 --> 00:54:06.620
You'd have to be careful.

00:54:06.620 --> 00:54:09.230
Don't ever use a cloth muzzle.

00:54:09.230 --> 00:54:12.320
You always want to use a big
basket muzzle if you do that.

00:54:12.320 --> 00:54:14.270
But I literally have
had clients do that,

00:54:14.270 --> 00:54:16.610
to literally protect their dog.

00:54:16.610 --> 00:54:19.310
Another thing you can do
is always teach your dog

00:54:19.310 --> 00:54:21.230
to sit in back of you.

00:54:21.230 --> 00:54:24.120
I do a lot of body
walking to people, lots.

00:54:24.120 --> 00:54:25.700
So I'd work with
a lot of dogs who

00:54:25.700 --> 00:54:28.949
are fear aggressive
to unfamiliar people.

00:54:28.949 --> 00:54:30.740
And when we're doing
conditioning programs,

00:54:30.740 --> 00:54:32.630
I literally-- the dog
was always back here,

00:54:32.630 --> 00:54:35.870
and I was always really quick
to body block the person.

00:54:35.870 --> 00:54:39.530
And sometimes you have
to be somewhat assertive,

00:54:39.530 --> 00:54:42.950
especially with dog lovers.

00:54:42.950 --> 00:54:45.410
And this is just
speaking as a zoologist.

00:54:45.410 --> 00:54:48.260
I will tell you that,
in general, women

00:54:48.260 --> 00:54:51.140
will ignore you and reach
towards to pet the dog,

00:54:51.140 --> 00:54:54.910
and say, oh, no, no,
no, dogs love me.

00:54:54.910 --> 00:54:58.160
I have a way with dogs.

00:54:58.160 --> 00:55:01.490
And guys are more
like, I'm not afraid.

00:55:01.490 --> 00:55:04.060
It's like, it's not about you.

00:55:04.060 --> 00:55:06.942
It's about the dog.

00:55:06.942 --> 00:55:10.080
So if I lived in New
York, then I literally

00:55:10.080 --> 00:55:11.954
would teach my dog--

00:55:11.954 --> 00:55:12.870
this would be the cue.

00:55:12.870 --> 00:55:14.520
And I wouldn't be a cue for me.

00:55:14.520 --> 00:55:16.170
I would start with a cue for me.

00:55:16.170 --> 00:55:18.030
So it would be like, back.

00:55:18.030 --> 00:55:20.570
And I would teach a dog, if I
see somebody about to do this,

00:55:20.570 --> 00:55:22.290
it would be-- so
your dog steps back

00:55:22.290 --> 00:55:26.250
and is a little bit behind you,
so you can always protect them.

00:55:26.250 --> 00:55:28.680
But turn it into an auto cue.

00:55:28.680 --> 00:55:31.920
So turn it into the reach
towards, is I'm going back

00:55:31.920 --> 00:55:33.690
and I'm sitting down.

00:55:33.690 --> 00:55:34.410
Wouldn't be hard.

00:55:34.410 --> 00:55:35.640
Really wouldn't be hard.

00:55:35.640 --> 00:55:36.760
So that's one thing to do.

00:55:36.760 --> 00:55:41.840
And another thing to do is from
a level of, oh, I'm so sorry.

00:55:41.840 --> 00:55:43.975
He's recovering from rabies.

00:55:47.740 --> 00:55:49.460
One thing I've done a lot--

00:55:49.460 --> 00:55:51.130
this is only if you have time--

00:55:51.130 --> 00:55:54.707
is I've said, you need time, and
you need to be far enough away.

00:55:54.707 --> 00:55:56.290
So I don't know how
much it would work

00:55:56.290 --> 00:55:57.520
on the streets of New York.

00:55:57.520 --> 00:55:59.349
It's like, oh, you
look like a dog lover.

00:55:59.349 --> 00:56:00.640
I know you're going to help me.

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:03.130
I know you know not to come up
and just reach towards the dog

00:56:03.130 --> 00:56:03.670
right away.

00:56:03.670 --> 00:56:05.294
Because you look like
a real dog lover.

00:56:05.294 --> 00:56:07.300
And nobody is willing
to say, like, I was

00:56:07.300 --> 00:56:10.420
about to reach toward your dog.

00:56:10.420 --> 00:56:11.799
So does that help?

00:56:11.799 --> 00:56:13.340
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
that's super helpful.

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:14.574
It's like, when they do ask--

00:56:14.574 --> 00:56:16.240
like, the people that
do the right thing

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:17.710
is the best way for,
like, greetings.

00:56:17.710 --> 00:56:19.720
Just like a hand out, and
letting the dog decide.

00:56:19.720 --> 00:56:21.470
PATRICIA MCCONNELL:
Yes, side of the face.

00:56:21.470 --> 00:56:23.830
So one thing you
can do is always

00:56:23.830 --> 00:56:25.660
good to give people
something to do.

00:56:25.660 --> 00:56:29.744
So you can say, oh, I would
love it if you pet my dog.

00:56:29.744 --> 00:56:31.660
But, you know, here's
what I'd love you to do.

00:56:31.660 --> 00:56:32.743
Would you take this treat?

00:56:32.743 --> 00:56:35.800
Put a treat in their hand,
and then you illustrate

00:56:35.800 --> 00:56:37.850
and say, give him
a treat like that.

00:56:37.850 --> 00:56:43.010
And so if you do it, half of
them will do what you say.

00:56:43.010 --> 00:56:46.270
The other half will just do it
totally wrong and then you--

00:56:46.270 --> 00:56:48.260
AUDIENCE: We'll start
with the get started.

00:56:48.260 --> 00:56:49.700
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Good
So you have one too.

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:50.324
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:56:50.324 --> 00:56:53.060
So I have a six-year-old
Dachshund, and he's a rescue.

00:56:53.060 --> 00:56:54.860
He's like Will--
I'd say, definitely

00:56:54.860 --> 00:56:59.450
traumatized, like, very
dog aggressive, except when

00:56:59.450 --> 00:57:00.470
I'm at the dog park.

00:57:00.470 --> 00:57:03.260
He's not that bad.

00:57:03.260 --> 00:57:04.820
On a leash, though, terrible.

00:57:04.820 --> 00:57:06.110
Like, very aggressive.

00:57:06.110 --> 00:57:06.800
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Classic.

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:07.510
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:57:07.510 --> 00:57:09.850
I've gone through
training with him.

00:57:09.850 --> 00:57:14.000
So he has a good foundation
of, I'd say, like, sit, stay,

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:15.180
go to bed, you know.

00:57:15.180 --> 00:57:16.774
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Good.

00:57:16.774 --> 00:57:18.440
AUDIENCE: But as far
as, you know, still

00:57:18.440 --> 00:57:21.720
being dog aggressive and even
with strangers, very aggressive

00:57:21.720 --> 00:57:22.940
with strangers.

00:57:22.940 --> 00:57:24.269
What are some--

00:57:24.269 --> 00:57:25.310
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Yeah.

00:57:25.310 --> 00:57:26.060
Oh, I hear you.

00:57:26.060 --> 00:57:28.670
First of all, yay for you,
for rescuing that pup.

00:57:31.580 --> 00:57:33.329
So here's the best
thing I would do.

00:57:33.329 --> 00:57:35.120
And I'll give you the
really short version.

00:57:35.120 --> 00:57:36.911
The longer version is
in a booklet I wrote,

00:57:36.911 --> 00:57:38.750
called "Feisty Fido."

00:57:38.750 --> 00:57:40.410
So basically, you're
going to combine

00:57:40.410 --> 00:57:42.590
operant conditioning,
Skinner's four

00:57:42.590 --> 00:57:44.900
quadrants of positive
reinforcement,

00:57:44.900 --> 00:57:46.980
plus classical conditioning.

00:57:46.980 --> 00:57:48.397
So the classical
conditioning part

00:57:48.397 --> 00:57:50.688
is that your Doxey is going
to learn-- what's his name?

00:57:50.688 --> 00:57:51.220
Her?

00:57:51.220 --> 00:57:51.810
AUDIENCE: Chaco.

00:57:51.810 --> 00:57:52.893
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Chaco.

00:57:52.893 --> 00:57:55.250
So Chaco is going to
learn that each movement

00:57:55.250 --> 00:57:58.790
towards him-- and so remember
to break it up into tiny steps.

00:57:58.790 --> 00:58:00.230
So say-- oh, I wish he was here.

00:58:00.230 --> 00:58:02.230
So say Chaco's there with you.

00:58:02.230 --> 00:58:03.967
So I'm your friend.

00:58:03.967 --> 00:58:06.050
And I'm one of your friends
who does what you say.

00:58:06.050 --> 00:58:08.450
So you eliminate half of them.

00:58:08.450 --> 00:58:10.670
Because we're people.

00:58:10.670 --> 00:58:12.920
So you would ask your friend
to walk forward one step,

00:58:12.920 --> 00:58:13.660
and then stop.

00:58:13.660 --> 00:58:17.420
And as he walks forward, you're
going to give Chaco a treat.

00:58:17.420 --> 00:58:18.545
And you might even--

00:58:18.545 --> 00:58:23.210
I like to put an operant
conditioning cue on it too.

00:58:23.210 --> 00:58:25.310
So before he sees the
person, you might say,

00:58:25.310 --> 00:58:27.470
Chaco, look at me.

00:58:27.470 --> 00:58:28.760
Or look at the person.

00:58:28.760 --> 00:58:30.414
Like, who is that?

00:58:30.414 --> 00:58:31.580
I actually taught Will that.

00:58:31.580 --> 00:58:33.360
It's like, who's that?

00:58:33.360 --> 00:58:34.940
So he looks at the person.

00:58:34.940 --> 00:58:35.680
Click.

00:58:35.680 --> 00:58:36.690
You can just say, good.

00:58:36.690 --> 00:58:38.440
You don't have to have
a clicker with you.

00:58:38.440 --> 00:58:40.391
But mark that behavior.

00:58:40.391 --> 00:58:41.640
And then you give him a treat.

00:58:41.640 --> 00:58:44.181
So first, you're going to teach
him an incompatible response.

00:58:44.181 --> 00:58:46.520
So if he's looking
at you, he's not

00:58:46.520 --> 00:58:48.810
going to be going
after somebody else.

00:58:48.810 --> 00:58:50.750
But at the same time,
as you work on that,

00:58:50.750 --> 00:58:52.430
as people get
closer, they're going

00:58:52.430 --> 00:58:54.110
to be the ones
throwing the treat.

00:58:54.110 --> 00:58:56.420
So it's step, throw.

00:58:56.420 --> 00:58:58.220
Step, throw.

00:58:58.220 --> 00:59:00.050
And so he's being
classically conditioned

00:59:00.050 --> 00:59:02.930
in a Pavlovian way, of,
like, person, chicken.

00:59:02.930 --> 00:59:04.220
Person, chicken.

00:59:04.220 --> 00:59:06.530
I am no longer afraid of person.

00:59:06.530 --> 00:59:08.780
But you have to
go really slowly.

00:59:08.780 --> 00:59:10.400
And what happens
is it's really easy

00:59:10.400 --> 00:59:13.290
to do the first steps right,
and then go too far too fast.

00:59:13.290 --> 00:59:15.500
And then all of a sudden,
your dog just bit somebody.

00:59:15.500 --> 00:59:18.470
So do it way slower and longer
than you think you need to.

00:59:18.470 --> 00:59:20.210
And you'll never be done.

00:59:20.210 --> 00:59:23.100
But just you can manage it, and
he'll get better and better.

00:59:23.100 --> 00:59:23.330
