00:59:24.920 --> 00:59:25.880
Thank you for being here.

00:59:25.880 --> 00:59:26.810
PATRICIA MCCONNELL:
Oh, thanks for coming.

00:59:26.810 --> 00:59:27.110
AUDIENCE: A couple of questions.

00:59:27.110 --> 00:59:30.122
I also have a rescue and
a lot of fear aggression.

00:59:30.122 --> 00:59:32.330
It's getting better, now
that living in New York City

00:59:32.330 --> 00:59:33.780
and having a lot more
exposure to people.

00:59:33.780 --> 00:59:35.405
PATRICIA MCCONNELL:
Yeah, good for you.

00:59:35.405 --> 00:59:38.120
AUDIENCE: But as a
result of anxiety,

00:59:38.120 --> 00:59:39.830
she would never
pee in the house,

00:59:39.830 --> 00:59:42.140
no matter how long I stay
and keep her in the house,

00:59:42.140 --> 00:59:44.110
eight hours should be fine.

00:59:44.110 --> 00:59:45.326
When I leave the house--

00:59:45.326 --> 00:59:47.450
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Oh,
she has separation anxiety.

00:59:47.450 --> 00:59:48.575
AUDIENCE: --she will do it.

00:59:48.575 --> 00:59:52.760
And I don't know how to explain
to her, how to help her not be

00:59:52.760 --> 00:59:53.720
afraid that I'm gone.

00:59:53.720 --> 00:59:55.110
I will be back.

00:59:55.110 --> 00:59:55.950
So that's one.

00:59:55.950 --> 00:59:58.550
And then secondly,
what is your point

00:59:58.550 --> 01:00:00.665
of view on e-collar,
electronic collars?

01:00:00.665 --> 01:00:01.790
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Oh, OK.

01:00:01.790 --> 01:00:02.960
Two questions.

01:00:02.960 --> 01:00:07.220
I'll answer the second one
first because that's quicker.

01:00:07.220 --> 01:00:08.359
I hate them.

01:00:08.359 --> 01:00:08.900
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:00:08.900 --> 01:00:11.399
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: I really,
really dislike them intensely.

01:00:14.360 --> 01:00:18.950
In 28 years or something,
I've used them twice,

01:00:18.950 --> 01:00:22.130
for dogs who were killing
livestock, and who's--

01:00:22.130 --> 01:00:24.620
the owners of whose
livestock had a gun,

01:00:24.620 --> 01:00:28.130
and were going to shoot the
dog if it happened once again.

01:00:28.130 --> 01:00:30.620
So that's the only situation
I've ever used them in.

01:00:33.830 --> 01:00:38.540
So back to your
separation anxiety.

01:00:41.200 --> 01:00:43.290
There's, again,
the longer version

01:00:43.290 --> 01:00:45.740
is a book that I wrote
called "I'll Be Home Soon."

01:00:45.740 --> 01:00:47.254
But the short version is--

01:00:47.254 --> 01:00:48.920
first of all, be sure
that's what it is.

01:00:48.920 --> 01:00:50.503
Because some dogs
are like she's gone.

01:00:50.503 --> 01:00:52.250
I can pee now.

01:00:52.250 --> 01:00:54.620
But if that's what
it is, then you

01:00:54.620 --> 01:00:56.030
need to start conditioning that.

01:00:56.030 --> 01:00:58.640
So basically, figure
out the trigger.

01:00:58.640 --> 01:01:01.340
So can you tell a time your
dog starts to get nervous?

01:01:01.340 --> 01:01:04.190
When you're getting your
keys, getting your coat,

01:01:04.190 --> 01:01:06.200
going in the bathroom
and brushing your hair.

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:09.620
Is there any sign she's getting
nervous as you're leaving?

01:01:09.620 --> 01:01:10.560
AUDIENCE: I think so.

01:01:10.560 --> 01:01:13.890
She's watching me every
move, following me.

01:01:13.890 --> 01:01:15.410
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Yeah, OK.

01:01:15.410 --> 01:01:18.140
So watch her really carefully.

01:01:18.140 --> 01:01:20.570
Start to see when she
shifts her behavior.

01:01:20.570 --> 01:01:22.040
And you'll see it.

01:01:22.040 --> 01:01:24.256
She'll start to
follow you around.

01:01:24.256 --> 01:01:25.880
And figure out what
is it you're doing,

01:01:25.880 --> 01:01:27.710
and use that as
your first trigger.

01:01:27.710 --> 01:01:29.840
So you're going
to condition her.

01:01:29.840 --> 01:01:31.160
Say these are my keys.

01:01:31.160 --> 01:01:33.289
So I'm going to pick
up my keys, and I'm

01:01:33.289 --> 01:01:34.580
going to throw a treat for her.

01:01:34.580 --> 01:01:36.080
And then I'm going
to put them down.

01:01:36.080 --> 01:01:38.080
And I'm going to do that
like 10 times in a row.

01:01:38.080 --> 01:01:40.580
And maybe part of the day, I'll
just pick up the keys and go

01:01:40.580 --> 01:01:42.210
sit on the couch and
watch television.

01:01:42.210 --> 01:01:44.480
So you deload the keys.

01:01:44.480 --> 01:01:45.560
And then you go--

01:01:45.560 --> 01:01:47.630
you do that for each step.

01:01:47.630 --> 01:01:50.480
Keys, coat-- every dog
has a different set

01:01:50.480 --> 01:01:53.900
of triggers-- walking to the
door, touching the door handle,

01:01:53.900 --> 01:01:55.580
opening the door two inches.

01:01:55.580 --> 01:01:58.100
You really do do this in
tiny little increments.

01:01:58.100 --> 01:02:02.000
And eventually, you go
outside for a second.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:04.550
And then you go outside for 10
seconds, then 30 seconds, then

01:02:04.550 --> 01:02:05.420
five minutes.

01:02:05.420 --> 01:02:08.226
The end goes way faster
than the beginning.

01:02:08.226 --> 01:02:10.100
Meanwhile, when you
really have to leave her,

01:02:10.100 --> 01:02:13.160
find a different
place, whether it's

01:02:13.160 --> 01:02:17.630
one room, a crate, or a
daycare, or something else.

01:02:17.630 --> 01:02:19.350
So you can separate
those environments.

01:02:19.350 --> 01:02:21.180
So that's the quick answer.

01:02:21.180 --> 01:02:22.350
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:02:22.350 --> 01:02:23.510
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: And I
can hang around a little bit

01:02:23.510 --> 01:02:24.710
afterwards if you have more.

01:02:24.710 --> 01:02:25.730
But I know there's--

01:02:25.730 --> 01:02:27.050
so hopefully, that
helps a little bit.

01:02:27.050 --> 01:02:27.320
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:02:27.320 --> 01:02:27.590
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Yeah.

01:02:27.590 --> 01:02:28.850
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

01:02:28.850 --> 01:02:29.808
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Hi!

01:02:29.808 --> 01:02:31.680
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:02:31.680 --> 01:02:35.370
So the other day, I
was playing piano.

01:02:35.370 --> 01:02:38.195
And my dog started howling.

01:02:38.195 --> 01:02:40.149
And he's never done that before.

01:02:40.149 --> 01:02:41.940
PATRICIA MCCONNELL:
You hit the right note.

01:02:41.940 --> 01:02:44.580
AUDIENCE: I was playing piano.

01:02:44.580 --> 01:02:48.090
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: So his
dog howls when he plays piano.

01:02:48.090 --> 01:02:49.140
I love it.

01:02:49.140 --> 01:02:50.580
Nobody quite understands it.

01:02:50.580 --> 01:02:52.800
But howling is contagious.

01:02:52.800 --> 01:02:55.350
Howling is a social function.

01:02:55.350 --> 01:02:57.990
We think it's sort of
like singing in church.

01:02:57.990 --> 01:03:00.420
It's a way of bonding
animals together.

01:03:00.420 --> 01:03:03.900
So you're just hitting exactly
the right note, that somehow

01:03:03.900 --> 01:03:05.690
is a salient trigger for a dog.

01:03:05.690 --> 01:03:07.440
Basically, your dog
thinks you're howling.

01:03:10.410 --> 01:03:12.510
So you can either--

01:03:12.510 --> 01:03:18.800
I would put it on cue, and then
do a video and put it online.

01:03:18.800 --> 01:03:21.300
So I think one more, and then
I know some of you have to go.

01:03:21.300 --> 01:03:24.720
But I can hang around, and sign
books, and answer questions.

01:03:24.720 --> 01:03:25.350
Yeah.

01:03:25.350 --> 01:03:25.950
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:03:25.950 --> 01:03:29.500
So I have an eight-month-old
Goldendoodle in the city.

01:03:29.500 --> 01:03:31.620
And we've had him
for four months.

01:03:31.620 --> 01:03:34.499
And he's scared of a lot of
things, but getting better.

01:03:34.499 --> 01:03:36.040
It's definitely
getting a lot better,

01:03:36.040 --> 01:03:37.470
like over the time
we've had him.

01:03:37.470 --> 01:03:40.685
But he's still like super
terrified of skateboards,

01:03:40.685 --> 01:03:41.590
especially.

01:03:41.590 --> 01:03:43.050
And there's a
couple other things.

01:03:43.050 --> 01:03:44.549
But it's like
definitely skateboard.

01:03:44.549 --> 01:03:46.502
PATRICIA MCCONNELL:
The worst, yeah.

01:03:46.502 --> 01:03:48.210
AUDIENCE: And I'm just
curious about what

01:03:48.210 --> 01:03:51.180
I should do in the
moment that happens,

01:03:51.180 --> 01:03:53.820
and he wants to just
freak out and run home.

01:03:53.820 --> 01:03:55.764
And my instinct is to
bend down and hug him.

01:03:55.764 --> 01:03:57.430
And I'm learning maybe
that's not right.

01:03:57.430 --> 01:03:57.830
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Maybe not.

01:03:57.830 --> 01:03:58.950
Yeah, right.

01:03:58.950 --> 01:04:02.666
I'll torture you
while you're scared.

01:04:02.666 --> 01:04:04.290
But you're a primate,
and you love him,

01:04:04.290 --> 01:04:07.380
and you're trying to
provide solace, right?

01:04:07.380 --> 01:04:10.290
First of all, skateboards,
this is, like, ubiquitous.

01:04:10.290 --> 01:04:12.390
I cannot tell you how
many dogs freak out.

01:04:12.390 --> 01:04:14.640
And I think it's partly
because of the vibrations

01:04:14.640 --> 01:04:16.260
and the low level noise.

01:04:16.260 --> 01:04:16.867
It's a growl.

01:04:16.867 --> 01:04:18.450
That's why dogs are
afraid of thunder.

01:04:18.450 --> 01:04:19.915
The world is growling.

01:04:22.970 --> 01:04:25.740
So this low-- it just
scares so many dogs.

01:04:25.740 --> 01:04:29.880
So you can't control
it, necessarily.

01:04:29.880 --> 01:04:32.100
When it happens, as
soon as you see one,

01:04:32.100 --> 01:04:34.110
you need to be, like,
on constant alert, which

01:04:34.110 --> 01:04:35.670
I'm sure you are already.

01:04:35.670 --> 01:04:37.410
So as soon as you
see one, you're

01:04:37.410 --> 01:04:39.785
going to move away as far as
you can, whatever that is.

01:04:39.785 --> 01:04:41.410
And then you're going
to ask for a sit.

01:04:41.410 --> 01:04:42.630
Good boy.

01:04:42.630 --> 01:04:43.155
Good boy.

01:04:43.155 --> 01:04:45.030
And then you're going
to give lots of treats.

01:04:45.030 --> 01:04:45.920
Good boy.

01:04:45.920 --> 01:04:48.120
And if he looks at
your face, good boy.

01:04:48.120 --> 01:04:51.720
I would teach a watch or look
at me, and do that separately.

01:04:51.720 --> 01:04:54.030
So get that down,
where it's easy,

01:04:54.030 --> 01:04:56.596
and it's not too scary for
him, and then go somewhere

01:04:56.596 --> 01:04:58.470
where you know you-- do
you have places where

01:04:58.470 --> 01:04:59.844
you know they're going to be?

01:04:59.844 --> 01:05:00.760
AUDIENCE: Skateboards?

01:05:00.760 --> 01:05:01.080
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: Yes.

01:05:01.080 --> 01:05:01.620
AUDIENCE: Central Park.

01:05:01.620 --> 01:05:02.994
I mean, they're
kind of sporadic.

01:05:02.994 --> 01:05:05.100
PATRICIA MCCONNELL: So
some predictability.

01:05:05.100 --> 01:05:08.090
So stay as far away as you
can, and say, do you see it?

01:05:08.090 --> 01:05:09.160
Where is the skateboard?

01:05:09.160 --> 01:05:10.660
Where's the skate--
name your fears.

01:05:10.660 --> 01:05:11.840
It helps with dogs too.

01:05:11.840 --> 01:05:14.340
Where is the skateboard?

01:05:14.340 --> 01:05:15.159
Where is it?

01:05:15.159 --> 01:05:15.950
Where is the thing?

01:05:15.950 --> 01:05:17.180
Where is the thing?

01:05:17.180 --> 01:05:18.660
And if he looks,
it's like, good.

01:05:18.660 --> 01:05:19.050
Treat.

01:05:19.050 --> 01:05:20.716
And then you're going
to back away, also

01:05:20.716 --> 01:05:22.350
to reinforce him,
because you're going

01:05:22.350 --> 01:05:25.590
to increase the distance
between him and that.

01:05:25.590 --> 01:05:26.670
So that's what I'd do.

01:05:26.670 --> 01:05:30.060
If you're blindsided, you
don't have time for anything,

01:05:30.060 --> 01:05:31.427
I would just walk away.

01:05:31.427 --> 01:05:32.010
Don't hug him.

01:05:32.010 --> 01:05:32.760
Don't pick him up.

01:05:32.760 --> 01:05:33.890
Just walk away.

01:05:33.890 --> 01:05:35.700
Get as far away
from it as you can.

01:05:35.700 --> 01:05:38.310
And then work your way
up to getting closer.

01:05:38.310 --> 01:05:39.330
OK, thank you all.

01:05:39.330 --> 01:05:41.470
It was really fun to be here.

01:05:41.470 --> 01:05:43.200
I love your dog culture.

01:05:43.200 --> 01:05:44.850
Thanks, Christine,
for asking me.

01:05:44.850 --> 01:05:46.750
And thank you, Alec.

